"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456714","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-04","<p>HMCTS does not collect data to the level of detail required to identify local authorities or social service authorities, or applications in respect of the Children Act 2004. The information can only be collated at disproportionate cost.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456714/answer",,,,,"29262 ; 29264 ; 29265","2016-03-04T12:28:24.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456714/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456714/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-03-01","Judicial Review: Local Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many applications for judicial review against local authorities in England related to those authorities' responsibilities under the Children Act 2004 have been (a) made and (b) successful in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Ms Karen Buck","Westminster North","Ms Karen Buck","29263"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456715","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-04","<p>HMCTS does not collect data to the level of detail required to identify local authorities or social service authorities, or applications in respect of the Children Act 2004. The information can only be collated at disproportionate cost.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456715/answer",,,,,"29263 ; 29264 ; 29265","2016-03-04T12:28:24.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456715/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456715/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-03-01","Judicial Review: Local Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many times local authorities in England have been subject to a judicial review of section 17 of the Children Act 2004 in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Ms Karen Buck","Westminster North","Ms Karen Buck","29262"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456716","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-03-09","<p>Information on whether cases with transferred arrears have a current liability on CMS is not readily available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>Information on transferred arrears is set out on Page 14 of the 1993 and 2003 Child Maintenance Schemes - Client Fund Accounts 2014/15 which can be accessed online at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/485960/HC687_Client_fund_1993_tagged.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/485960/HC687_Client_fund_1993_tagged.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456716/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-09T14:15:53.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456716/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456716/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-01","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what amount of child maintenance arrears accrued on the 1993 and 2003 schemes has been transferred to the 2012 scheme for collection in relation to 1 April 2015 (a) cases with a current CMS liability order and (b) cases with not current CMS liability order.","false","Biography information for Ms Karen Buck","Westminster North","Ms Karen Buck","29355"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456717","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-03-09","<p>The Child Maintenance Service is committed to ensuring parents fulfil their obligation to make financial provision for their children. The approach to the collection of arrears was set out in the DWP Child Maintenance Arrears and Compliance Strategy, <em>Preparing for the future, tackling the past</em> published on 31 January 2013.</p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456717/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-09T14:19:15.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456717/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456717/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-01","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether the Child Maintenance Service (CMS) gives the same priority for collection to arrears owed to parent with care who transfers from the Child Support Agency to the CMS by a paying parent as new arrears which accumulate under the 2012 scheme.","false","Biography information for Ms Karen Buck","Westminster North","Ms Karen Buck","29358"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456718","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-03-09","<p>Information on the number of cases with transitioned arrears from the 1993 or 2003 schemes is not readily available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456718/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-09T17:28:14.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456718/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456718/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-01","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many cases on the Child Maintenance Service system have child maintenance arrears, due to be paid by the non-resident parent, which were incurred under the 1993 or 2003 child maintenance schemes.","false","Biography information for Ms Karen Buck","Westminster North","Ms Karen Buck","29356"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456719","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-03-09","<p>Information on payment schedules is not readily available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456719/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-09T14:13:43.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456719/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456719/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-01","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many Child Maintenance Service (CMS) cases groups paying (a) by direct pay and (b) via the CMS collection service have a payment schedule which contains an amount in respect of Child Support Agency child maintenance arrears in addition to their current liability.","false","Biography information for Ms Karen Buck","Westminster North","Ms Karen Buck","29357"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456720","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-04","<p>This information is not held centrally and can only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>The National Crime Agency publishes statistics on the operation of the European Arrest Warrant and these can be found here: <a href="http://www.nationalcrimeagency.gov.uk/publications/european-arrest-warrant-statistics/wanted-by-the-uk-european-arrest-warrant-statistics/608-wanted-by-the-uk-european-arrest-warrant-statistics-2009-april-2015-1" target="_blank">http://www.nationalcrimeagency.gov.uk/publications/european-arrest-warrant-statistics/wanted-by-the-uk-european-arrest-warrant-statistics/608-wanted-by-the-uk-european-arrest-warrant-statistics-2009-april-2015-1</a></p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456720/answer",,,,,"29260","2016-03-04T14:01:36.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456720/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456720/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-03-01","European Arrest Warrants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the total number of years is that offenders brought back to the UK under a European Arrest Warrant have been sentenced to in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","29259"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456721","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-04","<p>This information is not held centrally and can only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>The National Crime Agency publishes statistics on the operation of the European Arrest Warrant and these can be found here: <a href="http://www.nationalcrimeagency.gov.uk/publications/european-arrest-warrant-statistics/wanted-by-the-uk-european-arrest-warrant-statistics/608-wanted-by-the-uk-european-arrest-warrant-statistics-2009-april-2015-1" target="_blank">http://www.nationalcrimeagency.gov.uk/publications/european-arrest-warrant-statistics/wanted-by-the-uk-european-arrest-warrant-statistics/608-wanted-by-the-uk-european-arrest-warrant-statistics-2009-april-2015-1</a></p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456721/answer",,,,,"29259","2016-03-04T14:01:36.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456721/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456721/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-03-01","European Arrest Warrants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many offenders have been sentenced and imprisoned in the UK after having been returned to the UK under an European Arrest Warrant in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","29260"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456722","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-04","<p>The decision by G4S will not have any direct impact on the day to day running of Secure Training Centres. G4S have committed to ensuring there is a smooth transition to new providers. We will work with G4S and the Youth Justice Board to make sure that happens.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456722/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-04T12:14:39.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456722/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456722/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-03-01","Secure Training Centres: G4S","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what his policy is on the sale by G4S of its Secure Training Centre contracts.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","29258"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456723","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-04","<p>The Government will be consulting on the detail of the proposals in due course.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456723/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-04T12:55:36.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456723/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456723/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-03-01","Personal Injury","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the compatibility of the changes to personal injury law and procedure announced by the Chancellor of the Exchequer in the Autumn Statement with the European Convention on Human Rights; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","29275"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456724","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-04","<p>Leading insurers have committed to give customers 100% of the savings made from new Government reforms to help slash the cost of motor insurance. Some have already made public their intention to do so.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456724/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-04T12:58:09.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456724/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456724/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-03-01","Motor Vehicles: Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 5 January 2016 to Question 20350, on motor vehicles: insurance, what information his Department holds on which insurers have committed to pass on all savings to consumers as a result of the proposed changes to personal injury law.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","29165"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456725","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-03-09","<p>Since the debate on 13 October 2014, neither the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond) nor I have had any discussions with Ministerial colleagues on this subject.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456725/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-09T17:38:27.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456725/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456725/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-01","Palestinians: Recognition of States","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with ministerial colleagues on recognising Palestine as a state since the House of Commons vote on this matter in October 2014.","false","Biography information for Jo Cox","Batley and Spen","Jo Cox","29323"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456726","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-03-09","<p>The British Government reserves the right to recognise a Palestinian state bilaterally at a moment of our choosing and when it can best help bring about peace. We are clear that we want to see the creation of a sovereign, independent, democratic, contiguous and viable Palestinian State, living in peace and security, side by side with Israel. Only a negotiated settlement can achieve this.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456726/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-09T17:39:43.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456726/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456726/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-01","Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what his policy is on the recognition of Palestinian statehood; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jo Cox","Batley and Spen","Jo Cox","29324"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456727","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-03-04","<p>We have not made any assessment of the potential effect of a UK withdrawal from the EU on the UK agriculture and fishing sectors.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456727/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-04T12:45:02.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456727/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456727/answer",,,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-03-01","Agriculture and Fisheries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the potential effect on the agriculture and fishing sectors of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Tom Elliott","Fermanagh and South Tyrone","Tom Elliott","29178"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456728","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-03-11","<p>When it comes to ensuring our families and businesses have secure, affordable and clean energy supplies they can rely on, the UK is better off being in Europe. The UK is leading the way in shaping EU energy and climate policies that strengthen our energy security, benefit consumers and help us tackle global climate change.</p><p> </p><p>Being a leading member of the EU helps improve UK energy security by attracting foreign investment, promoting competition and facilitating efficient and reliable cross-border energy trade.</p><p> </p><p>Unless the UK is prepared to be an EU rule-taker, keeping in lock-step with evolving EU energy and low carbon rules without any say on them, being outside the EU would create real and growing risks to energy security, consumer bills, and competitiveness.</p><p> </p>","Hastings and Rye","Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456728/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-11T15:00:44.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456728/answer","Biography information for Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456728/answer",,,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-03-01","Energy Supply: UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment she has made of the potential effect on energy security of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Tom Elliott","Fermanagh and South Tyrone","Tom Elliott","29179"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456729","Department for International Development","false","2016-03-08","<p>At the February European Council, the Government negotiated a new settlement, giving the United Kingdom a special status in a reformed European Union. The Government's position, as set out by the Prime Minister to the House on 22 February, is that the UK will be stronger, safer and better off remaining in a reformed EU.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456729/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-08T17:42:35.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456729/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456729/answer",,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-03-01","UK Membership of EU: Referendums","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the potential effect on the UK's international development capabilities of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Tom Elliott","Fermanagh and South Tyrone","Tom Elliott","29176"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456730","Scotland Office","false","2016-03-08","<p>At the February European Council, the Government negotiated a new settlement, giving the United Kingdom a special status in a reformed European Union. The Government's position, as set out by the Prime Minister to the House on 22 February, is that the UK will be stronger, safer and better off remaining in a reformed EU.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456730/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-08T16:14:01.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456730/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456730/answer",,,,,,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-03-01","UK Membership of EU: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what assessment he has made of the potential effect on Scotland of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Tom Elliott","Fermanagh and South Tyrone","Tom Elliott","29175"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456731","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-03-08","<p>The Government has published three papers which explain why the UK, including Northern Ireland, would be stronger, safer and better off remaining as a member of a reformed EU. The papers are available at <a href="http://www.gov.uk/publications" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/publications</a>.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456731/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-08T15:39:23.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456731/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456731/answer",,,,,,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-03-01","UK Membership of EU: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what assessment she has made of the potential effect on Northern Ireland of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Tom Elliott","Fermanagh and South Tyrone","Tom Elliott","29177"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456732","Wales Office","false","2016-03-08","<p>At the February European Council, the Government negotiated a new settlement, giving the United Kingdom a special status in a reformed European Union. The Government's position, as set out by the Prime Minister to the House on 22 February, is that the UK – including Wales – will be stronger, safer and better off remaining in a reformed EU.</p>","Preseli Pembrokeshire","Stephen Crabb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456732/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-08T13:10:27.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456732/answer","Biography information for Stephen Crabb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456732/answer",,,,,,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-03-01","UK Membership of EU: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what assessment he has made of the potential effect on Wales of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Tom Elliott","Fermanagh and South Tyrone","Tom Elliott","29174"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456733","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-04","<p>Published estimates of numbers of taxpayers, total income and total tax, broken down by income sources and parliamentary constituencies are available from the National Statistics Personal Incomes Statistics release.</p><p> </p><p>Information from 2010-11 to 2012-13 is available at the link below.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/income-and-tax-by-parliamentary-constituency-2010-to-2011" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/income-and-tax-by-parliamentary-constituency-2010-to-2011</a></p><p> </p><p>Information for earlier years is available at the link below.</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20120609145917/http:/hmrc.gov.uk/stats/income_distribution/menu-by-year.htm#315" target="_blank">http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20120609145917/http://hmrc.gov.uk/stats/income_distribution/menu-by-year.htm#315</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p>------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456733/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-04T14:19:54.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456733/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456733/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-01","Income Tax: Devon","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many people paid the (a) top rate, (b) higher rate and (c) basic rate of income tax in (i) Plymouth Moor View, (ii) Plymouth Sutton and Devonport and (iii) South West Devon constituency in each of the last five years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Johnny Mercer","Plymouth, Moor View","Johnny Mercer","29147"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456734","Department of Health","false","2016-03-04","<p>Local councils will receive £16 billion over the next five years for public health and have a duty to consider how best to respond to local public health challenges. Public Health England provides a range of resources to support councils in developing of tobacco control programmes. Decisions on commissioning services are for local councils.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456734/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-04T12:57:53.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456734/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456734/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-01","Smoking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 25 February 2016 to Question 27774, if his Department will take steps to ensure the funding for local smoking cessation services is maintained in (a) Barnsley Central constituency, (b) Yorkshire and the Humber and (c) the UK.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","29157"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456735","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-11","<p>As part of my Ministerial duties I visit local authorities across the country, including regular visit in connection with the Northern Powerhouse.</p>","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456735/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-11T13:40:47.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456735/answer","Biography information for Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456735/answer","Tunbridge Wells","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark","Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456735/answer/previousversion/49145","Biography information for Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456735/answer/previousversion/49145","Biography information for Greg Clark","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-03-01","Regional Planning and Development: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 25 February 2016 to Question 27333, which local authorities he has visited in connection with the Northern Powerhouse.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","29158"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456736","Department for Education","false","2016-03-09","<p>Throughout the introduction of our important reforms to primary assessment, we have worked closely with teachers, head teachers and their union representatives. Recently, these discussions have focused on primary schools adjusting to our new, more rigorous standards and particularly to the use of the new interim teacher assessment frameworks.</p><p>The Department has received recent correspondence on these issues from teachers and head teachers, to which we are responding. There have also been two e-petitions to cancel both the Key Stage 1 and Key Stage 2 tests in light of the new arrangements, which reached 10,000 signatures and will receive written Government responses shortly.</p><p>On 9 February, I met Russell Hobby, General Secretary of the National Association of Head Teachers, to discuss teacher assessment arrangements. I subsequently wrote to Mr Hobby to summarise our discussion and address some of his concerns; that letter was published on 19 February and can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/teacher-assessments-letter-from-nick-gibb-to-the-naht" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/teacher-assessments-letter-from-nick-gibb-to-the-naht</a>. This letter included confirmation that I have agreed to introduce a revised deadline of 30 June for teacher assessment submission this year in recognition of the unique circumstance of teachers working with a new framework to new standards.</p><p>In February, the Department has also received separate letters from Deborah Lawson, General Secretary of Voice; Mary Bousted, General Secretary of the Association of Teachers and Lecturers (ATL); and Christine Blower, General Secretary of the National Union of Teachers (NUT). I will be responding shortly and I am due to meet representatives from ATL and NUT in the coming weeks.</p><p>Specifically, concerns have been made about the example materials of pupils’ work that the Standards and Testing Agency (STA) published in January and February. These are designed to support teachers in making their judgements and I have asked STA to produce a clarification document to address any misunderstandings.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456736/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-09T16:12:00.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456736/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456736/answer","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456736/answer/previousversion/49285","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456736/answer/previousversion/49285","Biography information for Nick Gibb","60","Education","Education","2016-03-01","National Curriculum Tests","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent representations she has received from teachers and teachers representatives on changes to assessment procedures at Key Stage 1 and Key Stage 2; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","29257"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456737","Department for Education","false","2016-03-09","<p>The Government supports the establishment of a new College of Teaching, a new independent professional body for teachers. The College of Teaching has great potential to raise the status of the profession and improve standards through: supporting teachers to access accredited, high quality professional development; setting standards to determine effective professional practice; and helping teachers to use evidence on ‘what works’ to inform their own practice.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456737/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-09T15:59:01.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456737/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456737/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-03-01","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment she has made of the potential effects of the establishment of the College of Teaching on (a) continuing professional development of teachers and (b) teaching standards.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","29218"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456738","Department for Education","false","2016-03-09","<p>The Government welcomes plans to establish a College of Teaching. We are working with the College to discuss what Government support could be helpful in the initial set-up phase of the new body.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456738/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-09T16:04:18.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456738/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456738/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-03-01","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what progress she has made on releasing funding for the establishment of the College of Teaching.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","29216"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456739","Department for Education","false","2016-03-09","<p>Officials from the Department for Education have met regularly with representatives of the trustees, and also with the ‘Claim Your College’ consortium of education organisations that led plans to establish the new professional body. The Department is continuing to hold discussions with trustees on what Government support would be helpful for the College.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456739/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-09T15:58:45.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456739/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456739/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-03-01","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what discussions (a) she and (b) officials of her Department have had with the trustees of the College of Teaching.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","29217"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456741","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-09","<p>The information requested in respect of individuals tried and convicted for violent offences in their own home could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>Youth offending has been falling since 2010. Compared to the year ending March 2010, in the year ending March 2015 there were 67% fewer first-time entrants to the youth justice system. However, reoffending rates are far too high and the care and supervision of young offenders in custody us not good enough. That is why the Justice Secretary has asked Charlie Taylor to conduct a review of youth justice. He will report back later this year with recommendations on how to improve the treatment of young people in our care.</p><p> </p><p>Table 1 below shows the latest available data on the number of defendants, in the requested age groups, proceeded against at magistrates’ courts and found guilty at all courts of exposure in England and Wales.</p><p> </p><p>Table 2 below shows the latest available data on the number of defendants, in the requested age groups, proceeded against at magistrates’ courts for offences relating to harassment in England and Wales.</p><p>Table 3 below shows the latest available data on the number of defendants, in the requested age groups, found guilty at all courts for offences relating to harassment in England and Wales.</p><p>Table 4 below shows the latest available data on the number of defendants, in the requested age groups, proceeded against at magistrates’ courts and found guilty at all courts of sexual offences in England and Wales.</p><p> </p><p>Court proceedings data for 2015 is planned for publication in May 2016.</p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="7"><p><strong>Table 1: Defendants proceeded against at magistrates courts and found guilty at all courts of exposure <sup>(1)</sup>, England and Wales, 2010 to 2014 <sup>(2)(3)</sup></strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p