"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456000","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-22","<p>£42,000 has been allocated to advertisements on the London Underground.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s new National Living Wage is a step up for working people, so it is important workers know their rights and that employers pay the new £7.20 from April 1<sup>st</sup>. The campaign will tell people about their entitlements and is targeted at employers, and workers currently earning the National Minimum Wage.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456000/answer",,,,,"30776","2016-03-22T15:48:32.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456000/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456000/answer","Grantham and Stamford","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456000/answer/previousversion/49026","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456000/answer/previousversion/49026","Biography information for Nick Boles","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-29","Living Wage: Advertising","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 23 February 2016 to Question 24849, how much of the budget allocated for the National Living Wage advertising campaign has been allocated to advertisements on the London Underground.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","28906"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456001","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-07","<p>The Department collects self-reported data on the ethnicity of apprentices, but not nationality. Skills Funding Agency funding can only be used for apprentices whose main employment or normal place of work is in England. In addition employers are responsible for checking that their apprentices have the right to work in the UK.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456001/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-07T14:36:08.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456001/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456001/answer",,,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-29","Apprentices: British Nationality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what proportion of apprenticeships created in 2015 were taken up by British citizens.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","28923"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456002","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-07","<p>We have recently been provided with legal advice commissioned by Unite the Union and are considering the points raised by it.</p><p>Over several decades the UK and EU have signed numerous trade agreements. These treaties have helped both UK and EU businesses grow and create high quality jobs. They have also ensured that it remains for the UK to decide how our public services are run.</p><p>The Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership (TTIP) will be no different. Decisions on how to deliver public services for the best outcomes for UK citizens are and will be made by UK governments, not our trade partners. My right hon. Friend the Prime Minister, the European Commission and the US Government have all confirmed this. The NHS is not at risk from TTIP or any other trade and investment agreement.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456002/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-07T11:53:27.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456002/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456002/answer",,,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-29","Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership: NHS","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the implications for his policies of the legal opinion by Michael Bowsher QC and Azeem Suterwalla on the potential effect of the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership on the NHS; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","28932"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456003","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-14","<p>Provider payments are made on completion of an apprenticeship framework. The final 20% of the rate will be paid when the apprentice achieves their learning aim.</p><p>We emphasise the benefits of completing an apprenticeship. At Level 2 and 3 these are very significant, standing at between £48,000 and £74,000 for Level 2 and between £77,000 and £117,000 for Level 3 Apprenticeships<sup><sup>[1]</sup></sup>. Higher apprentices could earn £150,000 more on average over their lifetime compared to those with L3 vocational qualifications<sup><sup>[2]</sup></sup>.</p><p>We are committed to improving the quality of apprenticeships to ensure that they deliver the training employers and apprentices expect, making them more likely to complete.</p><p>Apprentices develop transferable skills and English and maths to enable them to progress in their careers. Employer-led Trailblazers are designing apprenticeship standards at a range of levels to provide the skills that employers need.</p><p>Ofsted is responsible for the overall process of inspecting and quality assuring training providers. The Institute for Apprenticeships will work closely with Ofsted, Ofqual and the Skills Funding Agency who have responsibility for quality assuring the delivery of many aspects of apprenticeships.</p><p> </p><p>[1] London Economics (2011) – ‘BIS Research Paper Number 53, Returns to Intermediate and Low Level Vocational Qualifications, September 2011’</p><p>[2] <a href="http://www.google.co.uk/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;frm=1&amp;source=web&amp;cd=1&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CCEQFjAA&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.gre.ac.uk%2F%3Fa%3D847246&amp;ei=yuISVM6wIIXearOwgMAB&amp;usg=AFQjCNEWM4DhlhjE1LrzYli9zpfdJccH8g&amp;sig2=_Q-Aau6esdAewP4ZPMVLFA" target="_blank">Apprenticeships in England Oct 2013</a></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456003/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-14T09:47:31.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456003/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456003/answer",,,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-29","Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he is taking to ensure that a greater proportion of people who start apprenticeships see them through to completion.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","28976"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456004","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-07","<p>Information on the number of Apprenticeship starts by region, Local Authority and Parliamentary constituency is published as a supplementary table (first link) to a Statistical First release (second link). Latest published data includes Apprenticeship starts reported to date for August to October 2015. Data up to and including January 2016 will be published at the same link following publication of the next Statistical First Release on 23<sup>rd</sup> March 2016.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/493777/apprenticeships-starts-by-geography-learner-demographics-and-sector-subject-area.xls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/493777/apprenticeships-starts-by-geography-learner-demographics-and-sector-subject-area.xls</a></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/learner-participation-outcomes-and-level-of-highest-qualification-held" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/learner-participation-outcomes-and-level-of-highest-qualification-held</a></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456004/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-07T14:36:51.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456004/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456004/answer",,,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-29","Apprentices: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many new apprenticeships were created in East London in 2015.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","28977"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456005","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-04","<p>The internal review of employment status has now concluded.</p><p>Ministers are carefully considering whether further steps are required to improve clarity and transparency for employers and individuals alike.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456005/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-04T14:21:01.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456005/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456005/answer",,,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-29","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 16 July 2015 to Question 6424, what progress his Department has made on its internal review of employment status, launched on 6 October 2014.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","29005"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456006","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-09","<p>The Dual Mandate for adult vocational education was published by the previous Government. Since the election of the new Government there have been a number of significant developments including: the commitment to 3 million apprenticeship starts between 2015 and 2020; the announcement of a levy to fund apprenticeships; the new Institute of Apprenticeships; the commission to Lord Sainsbury to review routes to employment; devolution of adult education funding and responsibilities to combined authorities; commitment to Institutes of Technology; the launch of area reviews; a spending review which has protected adult education from further cuts.</p><p> </p><p>Taken together these amount to a sea change in the Government approach to Professional and Technical Education and associated landscape. We have used the responses to the Dual Mandate to shape our thinking and will continue to do so.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456006/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-09T15:09:26.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456006/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456006/answer","Grantham and Stamford","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456006/answer/previousversion/49027","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456006/answer/previousversion/49027","Biography information for Nick Boles","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-29","Adult Education: Public Consultation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, when his Department plans to publish a response to his Department's consultation, A dual mandate for adult vocational education, which closed in June 2015.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","29011"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456007","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-03","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>No. Funding for basic skills is a crucial part of the Adult Education Budget. But a ring-fence means central Government deciding how money should be spent. We prefer to allow colleges and other providers to decide how best to meet the needs of the communities they serve. The interests of learners who lack basic skills are protected by statutory entitlements to free provision in basic English and maths.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456007/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-03T17:14:38.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456007/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456007/answer",,,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-29","Basic Skills: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether he plans to ring-fence funding for adult basic skills within the adult skills budget for 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","29012"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456008","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-03","<p>The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills is in regular contact with Ofsted both at Ministerial and official level to discuss the performance of further education (FE) colleges and providers. This includes the extent to which teaching, learning and assessment support adult learners to develop their skills in English and maths.</p><p> </p><p>Together with Department for Education, we have invested over £30m over the past 3 years to fund a range of measures to improve the further education workforce, with a focus on improving the teaching of English and maths. This has resulted in over 1,000 bursaries to attract graduates to teach in further education and over 3,800 existing FE teachers have benefited from training to improve their capability to teach high quality English and maths courses.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456008/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-03T17:13:14.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456008/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456008/answer",,,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-29","Basic Skills: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what discussions he has had with Ofsted on assessing the quality of teaching English and mathematics in adult basic skills courses undertaken by (a) further education providers and (b) other providers.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","29013"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456009","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-03","<p>Apprenticeships are jobs, so employers themselves decide what occupations and levels they employ apprentices in.</p><p> </p><p>Employer-led Trailblazers are designing apprenticeship standards at a range of levels to meet the skill needs of their industries.</p><p> </p><p>We will continue to encourage the growth of apprenticeships at all levels to meet our commitment to 3 million new starts in England by 2020, including Level 3, Level 4 and Degree Apprenticeships.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456009/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-03T17:06:14.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456009/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456009/answer",,,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-29","Sector Skills Councils: Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will hold discussions with individual sector skills councils on the proportion of the three million new apprenticeships that need to be at level 3 and level 4.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","29014"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456010","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-16","<p>The Government is considering carefully the Migration Advisory Committee’s recommendations on the rate and scope of the Immigration Skills Charge. In advance of finalising the regulations that will introduce the charge from April 2017, we will take account of evidence about the likely impact on different types of organisation, including universities.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456010/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-16T11:53:55.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456010/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456010/answer","Grantham and Stamford","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456010/answer/previousversion/49028","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456010/answer/previousversion/49028","Biography information for Nick Boles","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-29","Universities: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the implications for UK universities of the proposal for a £1,000 a year levy on all businesses employing skilled non-EU staff.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","29015"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456011","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-07","<p>Legal advice the Government has received in relation to the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership (TTIP) is subject to legal professional privilege and as such is not disclosable. This is a well-established principle which there is compelling public interest in upholding.</p><p>It is essential for the effective conduct of the Government’s business that ministers are able to seek candid advice from their lawyers and to discuss and debate possible policy options fully. They are less likely to hold full and frank discussions with their legal advisers if there is an expectation that the advice will subsequently be disclosable.</p><p>We do not maintain records of the total cost of the legal advice.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456011/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-07T11:54:25.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456011/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456011/answer",,,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-29","Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership: NHS","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what legal advice the Government has sought on the potential effect of the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership on the NHS; what the cost was to the public purse of provision of such advice; and if he will publish the legal advice on this matter his Department has received.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","29016"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456012","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-03","<p>We do not have any estimates on the scale of public fraud carried out by individuals or by serious and organised criminals in relation to identity theft or the creation of fake identities.</p><p>In the financial year 2014/15, £4.13m worth of detected external identity theft was reported to the Cabinet Office through the fraud and error MI collection. Identity theft includes: fraudulently obtained genuine documents; counterfeit documents; and, forged documents. We do not have a breakdown of whether this was committed by individuals or organised criminals.</p><p>The National Crime Agency, not the Cabinet Office, lead on matters related to serious and organised crime.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456012/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-03T10:29:15.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456012/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456012/answer",,,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-29","Public Sector: Personation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate he has made of the scale of fraud carried out against the public sector by (a) individuals and (b) serious and organised criminals by means of (i) identity theft and (ii) creation of fake identities.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","28950"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456013","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-07","<p>This information is not held and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456013/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-07T13:06:40.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456013/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456013/answer",,,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-29","Government Departments: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the (a) average and (b) total cost incurred by a Government department was of replying by letter to hon. Members raising matters of policy or casework with that Department in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","28897"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456014","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-03","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456014/answer","28893 table FINAL.xlsx ; 28893 FINAL.pdf","28893 table FINAL.xlsx ; 28893 FINAL.pdf","Excel Attachment for Member ; UKSA Letter to Member - Death from Liver Disease","Excel Attachment for Member ; UKSA Letter to Member - Death from Liver Disease",,"2016-03-03T16:44:29.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456014/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456014/answer",,,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-29","Liver Diseases: Death","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many people died from liver disease in (a) England and (b) each parliamentary constituency in the most recent year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for John Glen","Salisbury","John Glen","28893"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456015","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-03","<p>442,000 individuals’ identities have been verified on <a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">GOV.UK</a> Verify and the service has been used 1,100,000 times. <a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">GOV.UK</a> Verify is not designed for businesses.</p><p>The current percentage coverage for <a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">GOV.UK</a> Verify, based on a representative sample by demographic group, is available here: <a href="https://identityassurance.blog.gov.uk/2016/01/25/estimating-what-proportion-of-the-public-will-be-able-to-use-gov-uk-verify/" target="_blank">https://identityassurance.blog.gov.uk/2016/01/25/estimating-what-proportion-of-the-public-will-be-able-to-use-gov-uk-verify/</a></p><p><a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">GOV.UK</a> Verify publishes information about its performance - including authentications - weekly on the performance platform:<a href="https://www.gov.uk/performance/govuk-verify" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/performance/govuk-verify</a>.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456015/answer",,,,,"28949","2016-03-03T10:28:59.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456015/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456015/answer",,,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-29","Proof of Identity: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate has been made of uptake of the gov.uk Verify programme for each socioeconomic group.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","28948"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456016","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-03","<p>442,000 individuals’ identities have been verified on <a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">GOV.UK</a> Verify and the service has been used 1,100,000 times. <a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">GOV.UK</a> Verify is not designed for businesses.</p><p>The current percentage coverage for <a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">GOV.UK</a> Verify, based on a representative sample by demographic group, is available here: <a href="https://identityassurance.blog.gov.uk/2016/01/25/estimating-what-proportion-of-the-public-will-be-able-to-use-gov-uk-verify/" target="_blank">https://identityassurance.blog.gov.uk/2016/01/25/estimating-what-proportion-of-the-public-will-be-able-to-use-gov-uk-verify/</a></p><p><a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">GOV.UK</a> Verify publishes information about its performance - including authentications - weekly on the performance platform:<a href="https://www.gov.uk/performance/govuk-verify" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/performance/govuk-verify</a>.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456016/answer",,,,,"28948","2016-03-03T10:28:59.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456016/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456016/answer",,,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-29","Proof of Identity: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many (a) individuals and (b) businesses are registered for the gov.uk Verify programme; and what the average number of authentications is for each such group interacting with Verify supported services.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","28949"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456017","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-03","<p>The land and property for disposals will be identified in due course.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456017/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-03T13:15:51.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456017/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456017/answer",,,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-29","Public Sector: Oldham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answers of 5 and 16 February 2016 to Questions 25342 and 26658, by when he expects the land and property for disposals to be identified; and whether he expects the decisions on the selection of that property to be subject to public consultation.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","28898"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456018","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-07","<p>Promoting diversity in the Senior Civil Service is a ministerial responsibility of the Minister for the Cabinet Office. Details of my Ministers meetings with external organisations are published routinely and can be found on Gov.uk. Details of internal meetings are not disclosed.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456018/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-07T13:07:25.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456018/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456018/answer",,,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-29","Senior Civil Servants: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many times the Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster has met officials of the Cabinet Office to discuss improving diversity in the Senior Civil Service in the last six months.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","28871"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456019","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-07","<p>The new clause is about ensuring taxpayers money is only used for the intended purposes. The use or otherwise of research findings is already set out in grant agreements. There should, therefore, be no effect on organisations, which are free to use other funding to lobby, but not to spend taxpayers’ hard-earned cash on lobbying.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456019/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-07T08:52:16.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456019/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456019/answer","West Suffolk","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456019/answer/previousversion/48999","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456019/answer/previousversion/48999","Biography information for Matt Hancock","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-29","Research: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment he has made of the effect on organisations commissioning academic research of his Department's proposed regulations that would prevent recipients of government grant funding for research in using that work to call for government policy changes.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","28820"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456020","Cabinet Office","true","2016-03-07","<p>The grants clause will help to ensure that grant funding is always used for the intended purpose. It will <ins class="ministerial">not</ins> prevent organisations from using their own privately raised funds to campaign as they see fit. Given the clear intention of the clause, To ensure taxpayers’ money is well spent, there are no plans to debate it at present.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456020/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-07T08:52:42.537Z","2016-03-09T11:03:02.363Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456020/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456020/answer","West Suffolk ; West Suffolk","West Suffolk ; West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock ; Matthew Hancock","Matthew Hancock ; Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456020/answer/previousversion/48997 ; http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456020/answer/previousversion/49287","Biography information for Matt Hancock ; Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456020/answer/previousversion/48997 ; http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456020/answer/previousversion/49287","Biography information for Matt Hancock ; Biography information for Matt Hancock","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-29","Lobbying","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to his oral contribution of 25 February 2016, Official Report, column 486, when he plans to bring proposals for an anti-lobbying clause in Government grant agreements to the House for debate.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","28850"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456021","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-08","<p>The Government published a consultation on proposals to reform fees for applications for a grant of probate on 18 February. Alongside the consultation, an impact assessment was published which included a sensitivity analysis that accounted for a range of fee avoidance behaviours. This will be reviewed again in the Government response. The consultation will run for six weeks, closing on 1 April.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456021/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-08T11:08:29.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456021/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456021/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-29","Probate: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the effect of the recent increase in probate fees on the number of people who seek to avoid such fees by moving property into joint names to remove the need for a grant of probate.","false","Biography information for Karen Lumley","Redditch","Karen Lumley","28786"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456022","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-03","<p><strong>Mineral rights (or ‘mineral estates’) will generally be owned by the person who owns the surface land, but they can be held separately. Rights in respect of some minerals, such as mineral oil and gas, are held by the Crown, or the Coal Authority in the case of coal deposits. </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>Where an individual owns mineral rights, the value of them forms part of their estate for inheritance tax purposes. </strong></p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456022/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-03T17:11:59.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456022/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456022/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-29","Inheritance Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether death duties apply to mineral estates; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","28797"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456023","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-03","<p><strong>The information requested could only be provided at disproportionate cost. </strong></p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456023/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-03T14:13:34.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456023/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456023/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-29","Welfare Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the average yearly reduction in a household's tax credit award was when repaying an overpayment from the previous financial year for each financial year since 2006.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","28848"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456024","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-03","<p><strong>The latest data on complaints about UK government departments is available on the Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman’s website: <a href="http://www.ombudsman.org.uk/reports-and-consultations/reports/parliamentary/complaints-about-uk-government-departments-and-agencies,-and-some-uk-public-organisations-2014-15/8" target="_blank">http://www.ombudsman.org.uk/reports-and-consultations/reports/parliamentary/complaints-about-uk-government-departments-and-agencies,-and-some-uk-public-organisations-2014-15/8</a> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>This covers 2014-15. Data for 2015-16 has not yet been published. </strong></p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456024/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-03T17:03:01.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456024/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456024/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-29","Treasury: Complaints","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many complaints about (a) his Department and (b) HM Revenue and Customs were received from members of the public by his Department so far in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","28849"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456025","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-07","<p>The Government has consistently said that disposing of our stake in RBS is the right thing to do for the taxpayer and the British economy. Returning RBS to private ownership will promote financial stability, a more competitive banking sector, and the interests of the wider economy.</p><p> </p><p>The first sale of government shares in RBS was conducted in August 2015, and raised £2.1 billion for the taxpayer. The government will continue to return RBS to private ownership and conduct further sales of RBS shares, subject to market conditions.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456025/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-07T11:11:10.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456025/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456025/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-29","Royal Bank of Scotland: Government Shareholding","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make an assessment of the implications for his policies on reducing the Government's stake in the Royal Bank of Scotland (RBS) of the (a) decision to defer the redemption of dividend payment by and (b) recent changes in the share price of that bank.","false","Biography information for Ian Blackford","Ross, Skye and Lochaber","Ian Blackford","28814"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456026","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-07","<p>The Government will publicise the scheme in good time ahead of its introduction through a range of digital and non-digital channels.</p><p> </p><p>HM Revenue and Customs will also work with the childcare industry and representative groups who interact regularly with parents to raise awareness of the scheme.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456026/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-07T11:17:28.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456026/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456026/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-29","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he has taken to ensure that parents are aware of his proposals on the introduction of tax-free childcare.","false","Biography information for Jenny Chapman","Darlington","Jenny Chapman","28810"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456027","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-03","<p><strong>The Government confirmed that Tax-Free Childcare will be launched from early 2017. To roll out the scheme in a safe and managed way, we will be gradually opening up the scheme to all eligible parents within 12 months.</strong></p><p> </p><p><strong>We will provide further details of the exact plans for this rollout in due course, in good time for parents and childcare providers to prepare for the introduction of Tax-Free Childcare. </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong>Once the scheme is fully open, we estimate that around 2 million families will be eligible for Tax-Free Childcare. And we estimate that up to 1 million families may take up the scheme in ‘steady state’. </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong>The Tax-Free Childcare system will be extensively tested with users before the scheme is launched.</strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456027/answer",,,,,"28807 ; 28808 ; 28907 ; 28908","2016-03-03T17:40:05.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456027/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456027/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-29","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when he plans to publish an updated timeline for the delivery of tax-free childcare.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","28806"
