"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456048","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-08","<p>In December 2015 we launched a package of measures to combat homelessness. These measures include a £5 million fund for the 25 local authorities facing the greatest pressures in moving people more quickly out of temporary accommodation and into a settled home. This package also included a number of measures on homelessness prevention. Further details can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/radical-package-of-measures-announced-to-tackle-homelessness" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/radical-package-of-measures-announced-to-tackle-homelessness</a></p><p>The Department is committed to combating homelessness and from 2017/18 we will also be devolving the current funding for the temporary accommodation management fee, with an additional £10 million for those areas facing the greatest pressures.</p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456048/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-08T16:53:01.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456048/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456048/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-29","Temporary Accommodation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he plans to take to reduce the number of homeless families with children living in temporary accommodation for longer than the six-week legal limit.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","29020"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456049","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-08","<p>We do not collect data on the numbers of children in temporary bed and breakfast style accommodation for longer than 6 weeks.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456049/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-08T16:54:02.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456049/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456049/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-29","Temporary Accommodation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many children were housed in temporary accommodation for longer than the six-week legal limit in (a) the London Borough of Lambeth, (b) London and (c) England and Wales in each year since 2010-11.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","29021"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456050","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-08","<p>As I said in my earlier answer, the Government is considering how these payments to veterans should be treated in the financial assessment for social care charging in future. That consideration is still ongoing and an announcement will be made in due course.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456050/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-08T16:45:12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456050/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456050/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-29","Social Services: Veterans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 16 February 2016 to Question 26311, if he will make additional funding available to local authorities to enable them to fully disregard military compensation payments from financial assessments for social care.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","28938"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456051","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-03","<p>46.3% of senior civil servants in the Department are women. This is higher than the overall proportion of women in the senior civil service.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456051/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-03T10:54:34.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456051/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456051/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-29","Department for Communities and Local Government: Senior Civil Servants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what proportion of senior civil servants in his Department are women.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","28960"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456052","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-03","<p>Council tax decisions are a matter for individual local authorities and we have not made estimates of council tax in individual areas for future years.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456052/answer",,,,,,"2016-03-03T10:56:18.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456052/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456052/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-29","Council Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 21 January 2016 to Question 28259, what estimate he has made of the potential cost to people who pay council tax of that tax in (a) Stevenage, (b) Hertfordshire and (c) England in (i) 2016-17 and (ii) 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Stephen McPartland","Stevenage","Stephen McPartland","28942"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456053","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-08","<p>All new Government policies which impact on local government are assessed for whether they will represent a new burden on local authorities, against the criteria published in the New Burdens guidance. The New Burdens doctrine does not apply to policies which apply the same rules to local authorities and to private sector bodies, such as the apprenticeships levy, the national living wage and changes to national insurance. The guidance is available at:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/new-burdens-doctrine-guidance-for-government-departments.</p><p>In setting the future funding settlement for local government at the Spending Review in November 2015, the Government took account of a wide range of factors, including some which fell outside the New Burdens doctrine but nonetheless represented new costs for local authorities such as the apprenticeships levy, the national living wage and changes to national insurance.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456053/answer",,,,,"28868 ; 28869","2016-03-08T16:52:10.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456053/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456053/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-29","National Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much the Government plans to provide each local authority to meet the cost of planned changes to national insurance.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","28867"
